    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Body divided into distinct vertical sections and lives buried in sand, the disc level with sand surface. Only 12 elongate, evenly-tapering, equal tentacles that are held spread flat against the substratum, like the arms of a clock. Body colourless to cream, tentacles pale with yellow-brown Y shaped markings at base and bands of white spots along upper surfaces.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_748",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Column about 10 mm wide and 50 mm in height.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_749",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa (a record from India unlikely this species).</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Restricted distribution between St Helena Bay and False Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_750",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Rarely reported species originally found in False Bay with a few subsequent reports up to St Helena Bay. Sits buried in course sand with the tentacles spread out on sand surface. No other information on biology.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_751",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Diet has not been examined, by assumed to feed on a variety of smaller invertebrates.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_752",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Not specifically known for this species, but most anemones can reproduce both sexually, but releasing sperm and eggs into the water, and can also divide by fission.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_753",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Low tentacle number, colour pattern on disc and habitat fairly distinctive and one of few regional anemones with so few tentacles. <i>Holoclava capensis</i> has similar habits, colour, and a confusingly similar name, but has 20 very short tentacles.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_754",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
